---

## Browser Setup with `@irys/web-upload-ethereum`

### Installation

Install the required packages:
```
npm install @irys/web-upload @irys/web-upload-ethereum @irys/web-upload-ethereum-ethers-v6 ethers@6
```
where `@irys/web-upload` provides the core functionality for uploading data to Irys.(no content)`@irys/web-upload-ethereum` enables Ethereum-based payments,(no content)and `@irys/web-upload-ethereum-ethers-v6` adapts Ethers v6 for Irys.

### Polyfills (for Vite)

Vite doesn't automatically polyfill Node.js core modules like `crypto`, `stream`, or `path`, which are required by the Irys SDK. You'll need to add polyfills:
```
npm install --save-dev crypto-browserify stream-browserify os-browserify path-browserify vite-plugin-node-polyfills
```

---

### Connecting to Irys in the Browser (Ethers v6)

The examples use Ethereum and the `WebEthereum` class. To change tokens, use one from the supported list:

```js
import { WebUploader } from "@irys/web-upload";
import { WebEthereum } from "@irys/web-upload-ethereum";
import { EthersV6Adapter } from "@irys/web-upload-ethereum-ethers-v6";
import { ethers } from "ethers";

const getIrysUploader = async () => {
  const provider = new ethers.BrowserProvider(window.ethereum);
  const irysUploader = await WebUploader(WebEthereum)
    .withAdapter(EthersV6Adapter(provider));
  return irysUploader;
};
```(no content)`WebUploader(WebEthereum)` tells Irys that the uploader runs in a web browser and interacts with Ethereum-compatible networks. The `.withAdapter(EthersV6Adapter(provider))` instructs the Irys SDK to use the ethers.js v6 provider for signing and payment handling, acting as a translator connecting Irys SDK operations with Ethereum wallet interactions.

---

### Connecting with Devnet (Testnet)

For devnet/testnet usage with an RPC URL:

```js
const provider = new ethers.BrowserProvider(window.ethereum);
const rpcURL = "https://rpc.sepolia.dev";
const uploader = await WebUploader(WebEthereum)
  .withAdapter(EthersV6Adapter(provider))
  .withRpc(rpcURL)
  .devnet();
```

---

### Uploading a JSON String

To upload a JSON string in the browser, you can serialize your data object using `JSON.stringify()` and add a `Content-Type` tag:

```js
const dataToUpload = {
  cipherText,
  dataToEncryptHash,
  accessControlConditions: getAccessControlConditions(),
};

const tags = [{ name: "Content-Type", value: "application/json" }];
const receipt = await irysUploader.upload(JSON.stringify(dataToUpload), { tags });
```(no content)You can upload strings, Buffers, or streams — not just plain text.

---

### Retrieving Uploaded Data

Once uploaded, your files are accessible forever at `https://gateway.irys.xyz/{id}`.(no content)Uploads under 100KiB are free.(no content)For larger uploads, you'll need to fund your Irys account.

---

